Numerical Integration

  1. Stochastic Approximation

Below, we consider the example of approximating two quantities in the Normal-Normal model specified on slide 8 of Lecture 7:

  • \(E[log(\theta)]\)

  • \(p(\tilde{y} \mid \mathbf{y})\)

First, generate data: in practice, we observe this data. But, for this example, we assume that our model is appropriate and that our data does arise from the N(\(\theta\), 2) distribution.

set.seed(123)
#first, simulate some data

#Draw from prior distribution
prior.thetas <- rnorm(100, mean = 0, sd = 1)

#Draw from data generating process (usually observed in practice). We will draw from the mean of theta given by the distribution of prior.thetas
y <- rnorm(1000, mean = mean(prior.thetas), sd = sqrt(2))

Approximating \(E[log(|\theta|) \mid \mathbf{y}]\)

approx.log <- function(S){
  theta.given.y <- rnorm(S, mean = (sum(y)/2)/(1 + 500), sd = 1/(1 + 500))
  result <- (1/S) * sum(log(abs(theta.given.y)))
  return(result)
}

#Try this for S between 100 and 10000
E.log <- rep(0, length(seq(100, 100000, 100)))
i <- 0
for(S in seq(100, 100000, 100)){
  i <- i+1
  E.log[i] <- approx.log(S)
}

#Look at the approximation as the number of samples from the posterior tends to infinity
plot(y = E.log, x = seq(100, 100000, 100), xlab = "Sample Size", ylab = "Approximation")

We can see from above that the approximation converges as \(S \rightarrow \infty\).

Approximating \(p(\tilde{y} \mid \mathbf{y})\)

approx.posterior <- function(S, N){
  #S = number of draws from the posterior distribution
  #N = number of draws from the data distribution
  theta.given.y <- rnorm(S, mean = (sum(y)/2)/(1 + 500), sd = 1/(1 + 500))
  density.y.tilde <- matrix(0, nrow = N, ncol = S)
  for(s in 1:S){
    density.y.tilde[, s] <- rnorm(N, mean = theta.given.y[s], sd = sqrt(2))
  }
  result <- (1/S) * rowSums(density.y.tilde)
  return(result)
}

#Sample 1000 times from posterior and get a distribution over 5000 samples

predictive.density <- approx.posterior(S = 1000, N = 5000)


#let's look at the histogram for this

hist(predictive.density, probability = TRUE, n = 50, main = "Predictive Density")
lines(density(predictive.density), col = "blue")

Rejection Sampling Example

First, create our posterior that we want to try to sample from. In this case, we want a Beta(3, 10) density.

knownDensity <- function(x){return(dbeta(x, 3, 10))} 
#show a plot of this
x <- seq(0, 1, 0.0001)
posterior <- knownDensity(x)
plot(y = posterior, x = x, type = "l", ylab = "Posterior density", xlab = expression(theta))

Now, we simulate from this using rejection sampling and the scheme we discussed on slide 15.

#Generating n samples from the density
Rejection.Sampling <- function(n, M){
  samples <- rep(0, n)
  for(i in 1:n){
    condition = FALSE
    while(condition == FALSE){
      theta <- runif(1, min = 0, max = 1)
      post.value <- knownDensity(theta)
      g.value <- dunif(theta, min = 0, max = 1)
      test <- post.value / (M*g.value)
      U <- runif(1, min = 0, max = 1)
      if(U < test){
        condition = TRUE
        samples[i] <- theta
        }
    }
  }
  return(samples)
}

Generate 1000 samples using rejection sampling

M <- 4 #our best guess as to the maximum value of the posterior density
random.draws <- Rejection.Sampling(1000, M) 

#Compare the two
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
hist(random.draws, n = 100, probability = TRUE, main = "Rejection Sampling Draws")

hist(rbeta(1000, 3, 10), n = 100, probability = TRUE, main = "Draws directly from Density")

qqplot(random.draws, rbeta(1000, 3, 10))

Importance Sampling Example

Here, we demonstrate importance sampling using the example described on Slide 22. The goal here is to approximate the conditional expectation and variance of a Normal(1, 1) using a t(3, \(\sqrt{4/3}\)) proposal distribution.

#The unnormalized density function for the true posterior
unnormalized.q.theta <- function(theta){
  result <- exp(-(theta)^2 / 2)
  return(result)
}

#Our proposal distribution
g.theta <- function(theta){
  result <- dt(theta, df = 3)
  return(result)
}

#Importance Weights
imp.weights <- function(theta){
  result <- unnormalized.q.theta(theta) / g.theta(theta)
  return(result)
}

##Estimation of the Expectation
S <- 1000 #1000 samples
#draw samples from t(3, sqrt(4/3)) distribution
thetas <- rt(S, df = 3)
expectation <- sum(thetas*imp.weights(thetas)) / sum(imp.weights(thetas))

expectation
## [1] -0.05618537
variance <- sum(thetas^2*imp.weights(thetas))/sum(imp.weights(thetas)) - expectation^2

variance
## [1] 0.9727306
#Replicate these approximations 1000 times and get a distribution

expectation.function <- function(N, S){
  #get N estimates using S importance samples
  expectation <- rep(0, N)
  for(i in 1:N){
  thetas <- rt(S, df = 3)
  expectation[i] <- sum(thetas*imp.weights(thetas)) /                     
                    sum(imp.weights(thetas))
  }
  return(expectation)
}

variance.function <- function(N, S){
  variance <- rep(0, N)
  for(i in 1:N){
    thetas <- rt(S, df = 3)
    variance[i] <- sum(thetas^2*imp.weights(thetas)) / 
                   sum(imp.weights(thetas)) -    
                   (sum(thetas*imp.weights(thetas)) /                    
                   sum(imp.weights(thetas)))^2
  }
  return(variance)
}

expectation.estimates <- expectation.function(N = 1000, S = 500)
variance.estimates <- variance.function(N = 1000, S = 500)

#Plot these side by side
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
hist(expectation.estimates, n = 100, main = "Expectation Estimates")
abline(v = mean(expectation.estimates), col = "blue")
hist(variance.estimates, n = 100, main = "Variance Estimates")
abline(v = mean(variance.estimates), col = "blue")
